Yes! One common mistake is trying to return a reference to a local variable from a function, like this:"
fn foo() -> &str {
  let s = String::from("bar");
  &s
}
This won't compile because `s` goes out of scope at the end of `foo`, so its lifetime wouldn't be valid outside. Instead, you can return owned types or pass references explicitly:
fn foo() -> String {
  String::from("bar")
}
or
fn foo(s: &str) { ... }
Understanding these rules will help you write safer and more efficient Rust code.
